{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 17:05:31.825160", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall L3 control/data plane: Healthy. All OSPF adjacencies are Full, core/distribution/server routes are present, ICMP reachability across subnets is good.\n- Application-layer anomaly: One specific client, host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.13), consistently fails to establish TCP sessions (HTTP/HTTPS) to the server farm (10.200.0.0/24), including the published load balancer 10.200.0.7. Other clients in the same subnet and elsewhere work normally.\n- Likely fault domain: Path or policy affecting host_2_1_1_1 specifically for TCP/80 and TCP/443 towards 10.200.0.0/24 (server farm), causing SYN packets to be dropped (silent) before a SYN-ACK is received.\n- Probable root cause: A selective L3/L4 filtering/ACL (or equivalent) applied on an intermediate device or at the server edge that drops TCP/80 and TCP/443 sourced from 10.2.1.13. Less likely alternatives include per-source firewall on a server-side node or an uncommon per-host path issue; DNS/routing/MTU are not implicated.\n\nFindings and evidence\n\n1) End-to-end reachability and routing\n- ICMP reachability is broadly good:\n  - get_reachability shows 0% loss and low RTTs between hosts, server farm nodes, and the load balancer.\n  - From host_2_1_1_1, ping to 10.200.0.7 (load balancer) and to 10.200.0.2 (DNS) both succeed with 0% loss (RTT ~1.5–4.6 ms).\n- OSPF control plane is stable:\n  - All FRR routers (router_core_1/2/3, router_dist_1_1, router_dist_2_1, server_access_router) report Full neighbor state with expected adjacencies.\n  - server_access_router routes: 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected; all campus subnets (10.x.y.0/24) learned via OSPF.\n  - router_dist_2_1 routes: 10.200.0.0/24 learned via core (eth0); 10.2.1.0/24 local on br0; other prefixes present and consistent.\n- No policy routing anomalies:\n  - ip rule on router_dist_2_1 and server_access_router shows only default tables (local/main/default).\n\n2) Service availability (server farm)\n- On load_balancer and all web_server_[0-3], port 80 is listening on 0.0.0.0 (netstat -tuln).\n- Firewall (iptables) defaults to ACCEPT on load_balancer, web_server_0, server_access_router, and router_dist_2_1 (iptables -S shows default ACCEPT and no explicit drop rules in filter table).\n\n3) Application tests from multiple clients\n- Working clients:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.x): curl to http://web99.local and http://10.200.0.7 succeed (TTFB ~0.2–0.34 s, total ~1.0–1.15 s).\n  - host_2_1_1_2 (10.2.1.10): curl to http://web99.local, http://web0.local, and http://10.200.0.7 succeed (total ~1.0–2.1 s).\n  - host_2_1_2_1 (10.2.1.11): curl to http://web99.local and http://10.200.0.7 succeed (total ~1.0–1.76 s); http://web0.local generally succeeds, sometimes slower (total ~1.0–2.04 s).\n- Problematic client (host_2_1_1_1 / 10.2.1.13):\n  - curl to http://web99.local and http://web0.local consistently timeout at ~5.0 s (starttransfer 0.000, indicating no handshake/response).\n  - curl to http://10.200.0.7 similarly times out at ~5.0 s.\n  - nc -vz -w5 10.200.0.7 80 and nc -vz -w5 10.200.0.7 443 both fail (rc:1).\n  - nc -vz -w5 to backend servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6) on port 80 also fail (rc:1). Note: direct backend access may be intentionally blocked by design, but the load balancer should be reachable.\n\n4) TCP state on the failing client\n- host_2_1_1_1 shows SYN-SENT to 10.200.0.4:80 (using nc), indicating SYNs are leaving the host but no SYN-ACK is received (ss output).\n- However, the client can establish TCP connections locally:\n  - A test to 10.2.1.11:8080 (intra-subnet) succeeds (nc rc:0), confirming the TCP stack and local access path operate correctly.\n\n5) Excluding other causes\n- DNS is not the issue:\n  - Pings to DNS server (10.200.0.2) succeed from the problematic host, and curl namelookup is fast on both working and failing cases; failures persist even when using direct IP (10.200.0.7).\n- MTU and PMTUD unlikely:\n  - TCP handshake (SYN/SYN-ACK) uses small packets; we observe timeouts before any TTFB/starttransfer.\n- Asymmetric routing unlikely:\n  - Other hosts in the same subnet (10.2.1.0/24) succeed; ICMP both ways to/from host_2_1_1_1 is reliable; OSPF routes symmetric and normal.\n\nAssessment\n\nAnomaly detected\n- Yes. A targeted application-layer connectivity failure affects host_2_1_1_1 exclusively: TCP (80/443) to the server farm subnets (10.200.0.0/24) does not complete the 3-way handshake. All other sampled hosts can reach the load balancer and front-end web service normally.\n\nFault localization\n- The fault is not in OSPF or general L3 connectivity (pings OK; routes correct).\n- It is not a general server-side or service availability issue (listeners present; other hosts succeed).\n- It is not a general subnet-level issue (a peer in the same subnet, host_2_1_1_2, succeeds).\n- Localization narrows to a policy or filtering element that specifically affects traffic sourced from 10.2.1.13 to TCP/80 and TCP/443 destined for 10.200.0.0/24. This could reside on:\n  - An intermediate forwarding node in the path from 10.2.1.0/24 to the server_access_router (e.g., access switch or distribution router), or\n  - The server-facing edge (server_access_router) or a server host, with a per-source rule that silently drops SYNs from 10.2.1.13.\n- Client-side host firewall is unlikely (iptables default ACCEPT; other TCP flows like 8080 intra-subnet work; SYNs seen leaving).\n\nRoot cause hypothesis\n- The most consistent explanation is a selective L3/L4 filter (ACL, ebtables, mangle/raw iptables rule, or similar) dropping TCP SYNs from source 10.2.1.13 to TCP/80 (and likely TCP/443) towards the server farm 10.200.0.0/24. Because:\n  - SYN-SENT with no SYN-ACK indicates silent drop along the path or at destination.\n  - Only one source host is impacted; others in the same L2/L3 segment traverse the same routing path successfully.\n  - Server-side filter or policy that targets 10.2.1.13 would produce exactly this behavior for 80/443 while still allowing ICMP.\n- Secondary possibility (less likely based on evidence): a non-filtering anomaly on the path that affects only this source, such as an uncommon ARP/neighbor entry targeting 10.2.1.13 combined with per-port filtering; this is disfavored because ICMP works bidirectionally.\n\nAdditional notes\n- Design requirement “backend web servers should not be directly accessible from the hosts” aligns with observed timeouts to 10.200.0.3–.6:80; however, the load balancer at 10.200.0.7 must be reachable, and it is not for host_2_1_1_1 (which is the abnormal behavior).\n- DHCP on host_2_1_1_1 is active (dynamic lease, short valid_lft), and default route is correct; no evidence of misaddressing.\n\nConclusion\n- Network-wide health: normal OSPF, routing, and ICMP connectivity.\n- Abnormality: host_2_1_1_1 cannot establish TCP connections to the server farm while peers can.\n- Localization: selective filtering in the path specific to 10.2.1.13 and TCP/80/443 toward 10.200.0.0/24.\n- Root cause: probable ACL or firewall policy (possibly outside the filter table or on a bridging/switching element) silently dropping SYNs from host_2_1_1_1 to the server farm’s HTTP/HTTPS services.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 18512, "output_tokens": 6924, "total_tokens": 25436, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 18304}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4864}}}
